<p>A year ago, <italic>Administration &amp; Society</italic> began a series of changes, many of them spurred by the launch of our online submission and review system in July 2011. Although the transition appears to have shortened the span of time from submission to initial decision, we simultaneously have experienced a dramatic increase in the number of manuscripts we receive, particularly from our international colleagues. As a result, we have been more thankful than ever to all our reviewers, new and old, for responding with such thoughtful and encouraging reviews to our more than 700 requests for feedback on manuscripts in the last 12 months alone. To date, more than 200 scholars have reviewed for us through the online system. These reviewers are the true unsung heroes of the academic world. The only reward for their time and effort can be awareness that they are performing one of the most essential tasks in the creation of new knowledge. We would like to acknowledge their contribution by listing their names at the end of this note.</p>
<p>The influx of manuscripts has led to additional changes that will affect our authors, reviewers, and readers moving forward. These include changes in page limits, publication frequency, and editorial staff.</p>
<sec id="section1-0095399712466318">
<title>Page Limits</title>
<p>Due to our growing submission rate, we have decided to reduce the total page limit per original article from 40 to 32 pages. This reduction will allow us to publish at least one extra article per issue compared with our current number, which will enable authors to see their articles in print sooner. In addition, we will be limiting Responses and Rejoinders in our <italic>Disputatio Sine Fine</italic> section to between 5 and 7 pages.</p>
</sec>
<sec id="section2-0095399712466318">
<title>Frequency</title>
<p>As with many other journals, the length of time between our accepting a manuscript for publication and when it appears in print remains a challenge. OnlineFirst, our feature that provides access to articles through our website, enables our authors’ research and contributions to see the light of day sooner. Despite online availability, we still find the length of the publishing queue to exceed what we consider to be acceptable. After consulting with our publisher, SAGE Publications has agreed to increase the number of issues per volume from 8 to 9 beginning in 2013 with Volume 45.</p>
</sec>
<sec id="section3-0095399712466318">
<title>Editorial Staff</title>
<p>Finally, our editorial office staff has undergone some changes in the past year. After 3 years as managing editor, Nicole Rishel is moving on to finish her dissertation and seek a position with some lucky university. She will be sorely missed. Her good humor, patience, and unfailing politeness have been much appreciated by authors and staff.</p>
<p>Meredith Hundley, who came onboard our staff last year as the editorial assistant, will become the new managing editor beginning with the October 2012 issue. Meredith led the way in the computerization of our review process. Her patience and skills were invaluable, especially in light of the lack of both qualities in the chief editor.</p>
<p>In addition, we welcome Noel Gniady to the staff as editorial assistant. Noel is a graduate of the University of New Orleans and holds a master of military science degree specializing in homeland security from the U.S. Army Command and General Staff College and master’s degree in information resource management from the University of Maryland. She has served as an Army officer with assignments that took her to Kuwait, Jordan, Qatar, and Iraq.</p>
